notes: Fourth-generation Camry. First Camry designed primarily for North American market. Became best-selling car in America. Available as sedan, coupe, or wagon. Manual transmission available. Data sourced from Wikipedia Toyota Camry article, January 2025 revision.

Fifth-generation Camry. Continued dominance of mid-size sedan segment. Available as sedan or coupe. Manual transmission on base models. Solara coupe variant. Data sourced from Wikipedia Toyota Camry article, January 2025 revision.

Legendary fourth-generation Supra. Twin-turbo 2JZ-GTE engine. Manual transmission available. Targa top removable roof. Cult classic performance car. Featured in Fast & Furious. Data sourced from Wikipedia Toyota Supra article, January 2025 revision.

First-generation Tacoma replaced Pickup/Hilux name in North America. Available in regular cab or Xtracab. Manual transmission available. Reliable compact pickup. Data sourced from Wikipedia Toyota Tacoma article, January 2025 revision.

First-generation RAV4 introduced to North America. Pioneered compact crossover SUV segment. Available as 2-door or 4-door. Manual transmission available. Car-like unibody construction. Data sourced from Wikipedia Toyota RAV4 article, January 2025 revision.

Third-generation 4Runner. Shift to 4-door only configuration. Body-on-frame construction. Available with I4 or V6. Manual transmission available. Off-road capable. Data sourced from Wikipedia Toyota 4Runner article, January 2025 revision.

J80 Land Cruiser. Legendary off-road capability and reliability. Full-time 4WD. Three-row seating. Body-on-frame construction. Known for extreme durability. Data sourced from Wikipedia Toyota Land Cruiser article, January 2025 revision.

First-generation Prius. World's first mass-produced hybrid vehicle. Introduced 1997 in Japan, 2000 in North America. Revolutionary Toyota Hybrid System. Pioneered mainstream hybrid technology. Hybrid system requires specialized service. Data sourced from Wikipedia Toyota Prius article, January 2025 revision.
